-- Mars Oil Premium Gains on Shell Gulf Coast Platform Shutdown
-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 2012-04-04T19:39:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-04/mars-oil-premium-gains-on-shell-gulf-coast-platform-shutdown.html
Mars oil’s premium to West  Texas 
Intermediate strengthened after  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  said it
will shut the Mars deep-water platform in the U.S. Gulf of
 Mexico  for maintenance.  Shell will perform the work in the second quarter, Emily Oberton, a Houston-based spokeswoman, said in an e-mail late
yesterday. The platform is about 130 miles (209 kilometers)
south of  New Orleans .  Mars Blend (USCSMARS) ’s premium to WTI increased 30 cents to $15.80 a
barrel at 2:05 p.m. in  New York , according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  Thunder Horse ’s premium added $1 to $18.75 a barrel
and Poseidon’s gained 35 cents to $15. Southern Green Canyon
widened 65 cents to $15.75 over WTI.  The discount for WTI at  Midland (USCSWTIM) , Texas, versus the same
grade at Cushing,  Oklahoma , widened for the seventh straight
session by 30 cents to $8.45 a barrel. Midland is about 480
miles from Cushing.  Light Louisiana Sweet’s (USCSLLSS)  premium added 25 cents to $22.50 a
barrel over the U.S. benchmark.  Heavy Louisiana Sweet (USCSHLSE) ’s premium
lost 15 cents to $23.35 a barrel.  West Texas Sour (USCSWTSM) ’s discount widened 45 cents a barrel to
$8.75 below WTI.  Western Canada Select (USCSWCAS) ’s discount widened 25 cents to $25 a
barrel. Bakken oil’s narrowed $1 to $10 a barrel below WTI and
Syncrude’s discount widened 75 cents to $4.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Aaron Clark in New York at 
